    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3937017825" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3937017825" />
    <a title="Max" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8079403-max"><img alt="Max" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1625519120p2/8079403.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3937017825?book_show_action=true">Apr 10, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Max" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Max" href="/user/show/8079403-max">Max</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8079403-max?shelf=current-events">current-events</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3937017825" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17878858701095541472">Levoy reports on the high rate of black men murdering black men in South and East Los Angeles between 2001 and 2012. She does not report on police killing of blacks, so much in the news as I write this. Covering the police beat for the L.A. Times, Levoy embedded herself in L.A. police stations, and spent a decade interviewing police, victims’ families, and witnesses, visiting crime scenes, attending funerals, and court cases, and just walking the streets in black communities dominated by gang vi</span>
  <span id="freeText17878858701095541472" style="display:none">Levoy reports on the high rate of black men murdering black men in South and East Los Angeles between 2001 and 2012. She does not report on police killing of blacks, so much in the news as I write this. Covering the police beat for the L.A. Times, Levoy embedded herself in L.A. police stations, and spent a decade interviewing police, victims’ families, and witnesses, visiting crime scenes, attending funerals, and court cases, and just walking the streets in black communities dominated by gang violence. She analyzes the crimes, criminals and communities with a focus on the L.A. police department. She profiles individual police officers and detectives, some favorably and some not. There is no stereotyping. Everyone is treated as an individual. She also profiles some of the criminals, the victims and most heartrending the victims’ families. One poignant case runs throughout the book tying her analysis together and giving us a true crime saga to maintain our interest. Levoy comes to clear conclusions on what type of policing works and what doesn’t. <br /><br />The murder rate had been tapering off considerably in L.A. since the early 2000s when Levoy was conducting her research, but spiked in 2020 with increased gang warfare. A 2020 nbclosangeles.com article I found about gang killings in South L.A. read just like pages from Levoy’s book. The murders Levoy describes were due to organized gangs. They often demanded members kill someone in an opposing gang to prove themselves. Retaliatory killings were endless. Sometimes a specific person was selected to be killed to settle a score, other times any gang member would do. Cases of innocent people not associated with gangs being killed by mistake or accident were common. Local citizens did not dare turn in or “snitch” on gang members since it would make them and their families the next target.<br /><br />Levoy blames the formation of gangs on lack of policing. Traditionally in America, law enforcement has not cared about black on black crime. With black communities left without policing, gangs rose to fill the vacuum. When police did focus on black communities, their methods were counterproductive, leaving gangs to continue their domination. Levoy doesn’t hold back her criticism of the L.A. police. She decries shows of force where uniformed officers randomly cruise the streets and conduct raids on small time offenders such as drug dealers, making a show of their presence, but failing to interact with the community. She finds police in gang units to be ineffective, neither preventing nor solving crimes. These just drain resources from where she believes they are needed, to support homicide detectives that are focused on the community and interact with people on the street. Working in plain clothes, their investigatory work gets them familiar with the community where they form relationships with the residents. The skill and dedication of individual detectives varies, but as a group in sufficient numbers with experience in the community and with sufficient resources they do solve homicides despite the serious obstacles in communities dominated by gangs. Levoy believes success in locking up perpetrators of murder is the best deterrent and is possible for an adequately resourced, well-organized and focused police force. <br /><br />Levoy put in ten years studying the issue firsthand, getting to know the community and the police. She convinces me that her views should be taken seriously. She cites improvements in LA policing following her initial research and the reduction in black on black murder rates, although changing demographics played a large part as many blacks left L.A. for the suburbs. Her book was published in 2015. As noted above the murder rate spiked in 2020. The book’s first hundred pages are devoted to reporting, analysis and opinion about policing and crime in South and East L.A. The rest of the book focuses on one particular murder that underscores her points about policing. It is a well written true crime drama. In it we see people, black and white, police and residents, as individuals, not statistics. Levoy does not extend her findings and opinions to other communities or other types of crime. Still I felt Levoy gave me some insight into life in a gang dominated community and how policing these communities could be improved and lives saved.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="17878858701095541472" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


